"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-07-31-olympic-duo-nasty-fall-out-best-player-world-branded-insincere-21337707\", \"text\": \"Olympic tennis starsIga Swiatekand Danielle Collins had a nasty fall-out on Wednesday, with the Polish world No.1 branded 'insincere' by her opponent.  Swiatek is the best current female tennis player in the world and is dominant across the WTA Tour, especially on clay, having won theFrench Openfor three straight years.  The 23-year-old has an incredible tally of 11,005 ranking points at the moment - 2832 more than the world No.2 Coco Gauff - showing just how strong she is.  Swiatek has been caught up in controversy, though, after Team USA star Collins slammed her following their tense quarter-final showdown at Roland-Garros.  During the match, Collins told Swiatek to 'play at the server's pace' after the Polish star held up her hand to halt the American's service motion.  Collins later appeared to hit Swiatek with the ball - and the world No.1 was also jeered onto the court for taking a long break at the end of the second set.  The American eventually retired to hand Swiatek victory - and following a heated exchange on the court - Collins ripped into the top-seed in her press conference.  'I told Iga she did not have to be insincere about, you know, my injury,' Collins said.  'There is a lot that happens on camera, and there are a lot of people with a ton of charisma and come out and are one way on camera and another way in the locker room.  'And I just have not had the best experience, and I do not really feel like anybody needs to be insincere. They can be the way that they are. I can accept that, and I do not need the fakeness.'  pic.twitter.com/vR5Bk80IN5  Swiatek has issued a response and has insisted that she has no idea where Collins is coming from.  'I will not argue about it, because I have never done anything unpleasant towards her,' Swiatek said. 'I just wanted to congratulate her on her successful career, because we all know that this is her last year on tour.  'Honestly, I do not know what she meant because we did not even have any interactions that could have caused her to say that to me.  'Generally speaking, during tournaments, when we go out and have time to change our clothes, we are entitled to five minutes. Here I asked the lady who escorted me how much time I had. She did not tell me that.  'She replied that they do not count time here and that I should just leave when I feel like it. So I used this time to change and cool down, and then I returned to the court.  'I honestly did not know how much time had passed, but I did not do anything against the rules, so I do not really know what the whole situation was about.'    ArrowMORE:Olympic triathlete makes disgusting revelation after swimming in polluted Paris river  ArrowMORE:Olympic gold medallist awkwardly squirms in confrontation over Strictly 2024 'leak'  ArrowMORE:Michael Phelps reacts to Leon Marchand's historic Olympic double gold in Paris  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"